Actually, wait. Let me think about this more carefully. The `showLoading` parameter might be intentional - maybe the caller wants to show loading UI before the API call happens. But the service always sets loading status anyway.

Looking at the old implementation:
```typescript
if (showLoading) {
  setLoading(true);
}

try {
  const result = await invoiceCashbackPermissionService.hasRedeemed(accountId);
  setHasRedeemed(result);
  return result;
} catch {
  setError(true);
  return false;
}
```

The old service didn't set any loading status - the hook did it all. So `showLoading` controlled whether the hook set loading status.

But in the new pattern, the service manages all status. So `showLoading` becomes meaningless - the service will always set loading status.

I think the right approach is:
1. Remove the `showLoading` functionality from the hook (breaking change but makes sense in new architecture)
2. Or keep it but acknowledge it's now a no-op
3. Or don't let service set loading status automatically, and let the hook control it

Actually, looking at the parameter service pattern, it doesn't have a hook at all - components call the service directly. And the service manages all status.

But our permission service needs a hook because it needs accountId from selector.

I think the cleanest solution is to keep the `showLoading` parameter but make it control whether we set status before calling the service. The service will always update status, but if showLoading is false, we start without showing loading.

Actually no, that doesn't make sense either. The service sets loading immediately.

Let me think about the use cases:
1. Component wants to check if redeemed, doesn't want to show loading spinner - calls with `showLoading: false`
2. Component wants to check if redeemed, wants to show loading spinner - calls with `showLoading: true`


But the service will always set status to LOADING, which will make isLoading=true in the hook return value. So the `showLoading` parameter is now meaningless! The best approach is to deprecate it for backward compatibility while letting the service handle all status management. I should check how it's actually used in the codebase to see if removing it would break anything.

